man origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Beckers","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ewald, Gerda, Hans, Klaus, Kurt, Wendelin, Wilhelmina.  French Jacques, Thierry.","Dutch, Flemish, and German: variant of   Becker   + the genitive case <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Baecker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegfried, Bodo, Gerhardt, Heinz, Horst, Kurt, Waltraud.","German (mainly <b>Bäcker</b>): variant of   Becker  . Compare   Backer  ."]},{"name":"Beck","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from northern Middle English <i>bekke</i> ‘stream’ (Old Norse <i>bekkr</i>).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of various places in northern France named Bec, for example Bec Hellouin in Eure, named with Old Norman French <i>bec</i> ‘stream’, from the same Old Norse root as in 1 above.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Becke</i> (Old English <i>Becca</i> or <i>Beocca</i>), of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Beckerle","meanings":["South German: diminutive of   Becker  ."]},{"name":"De Beck","meanings":["Flemish: short form of <b>De Becker</b>, see   Becker  , or a variant of   Beckman  ."]},{"name":"Beckermann","meanings":["German: variant of   Becker   ‘baker’, formed with Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Hanss","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Johannes ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hansel","meanings":["Pet form of   Johannes ."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hanss Peter Becker was born on 16 March 1645, in Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany as the son of Matthias Becker. He married Anna Geraitt about 1670, in Germany. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"16 March 1645–":"16. märts 1645–Surnud","1645–Male":"1645–Surnud","1647–Female":"1647–Surnud","1662–1745":"1662–1745","1666–1750":"1666–1750","1671–1748":"1671–1748","1603–1603":"1603–1603","16 Mar 1645":"16. märts 1645","1671":"1671","5 November 1671":"5. november 1671","ABT 1666":"umbes 1666","Dec 1662":"detsember 1662","1745":"1745","1645":"1645","1666":"1666","1750":"1750","1662":"1662","16 March 1645":"16. märts 1645","1748":"1748","about 1670":"umbes 1670","1603":"1603","1647":"1647","Framersheim, Rhineland-Pfatz, Germany":"Framersheim, Landkreis Alzey-Worms, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa",",, Germany":"Saksamaa","Traben, Zell, Rhein, Preußen, Deutschland":"Traben, Zell, Rheinprovinz, Preußen, Saksamaa","Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Framersheim, Landkreis Alzey-Worms, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Germany":"Saksamaa"},"fi":{"16 March 1645–":"16. maaliskuuta 1645–Kuollut","1645–Male":"1645–Kuollut","1647–Female":"1647–Kuollut","1662–1745":"1662–1745","1666–1750":"1666–1750","1671–1748":"1671–1748","1603–1603":"1603–1603","16 Mar 1645":"16. maaliskuuta 1645","1671":"1671","5 November 1671":"5. marraskuuta 1671","ABT 1666":"noin 1666","Dec 1662":"joulukuu 1662","1745":"1745","1645":"1645","1666":"1666","1750":"1750","1662":"1662","16 March 1645":"16. ma